Rakos Knowledge Sync Publishing Rules

Source of truth

- The Markdown repo is the source of truth for knowledge content.
- WordPress is the publishing target.
- Do not patch previous broken WordPress output by hand. Rebuild from repo data.

Confirmed live WordPress model

- CPT key: `knowledge-page`
- Public URL pattern: `/knowledge/[slug]/`
- Taxonomy keys:
  - `knowledge-type`
  - `knowledge-topic`
  - `knowledge-industry`
  - `knowledge-framework`

Confirmed live ACF fields

- `repo_file_path`
- `repo_slug`
- `repo_last_updated`
- `github_source_url`
- `knowledge_title`
- `primary_entity`
- `schema_type`
- `word_count_target`
- `related_services`
- `related_concepts`
- `source_urls`
- `suggested_schema_type`
- `supporting_schema_types`
- `schema_json_override`
- `internal_link_suggestions`
- `related_knowledge_pages`
- `soft_cta_text`
- `soft_cta_button_text`
- `soft_cta_button_url`

Important field notes

- `related_frameworks` is not a live ACF field.
- `related_industries` is not a live ACF field.
- Frameworks and industries must still be assigned through taxonomy:
  - `knowledge-framework`
  - `knowledge-industry`

Public post content rules

- `post_content` must contain only clean classic HTML for the human-readable article.
- Do not store Gutenberg block markup.
- Do not store repo-only sections as visible article content.
- Do not store JSON-LD schema in `post_content`.

Publish these sections visibly when present

- Definition
- Why It Matters
- How Rakos Media Group Thinks About This
- Main topic sections
- Business Impact
- Related Entities when appropriate
- FAQ
- Related Knowledge block

Do not publish these sections visibly

- YAML frontmatter
- Suggested Schema Type
- Suggested supporting schema
- Internal Link Suggestions
- Source URLs unless intentionally used as visible references
- Private notes
- Raw schema instructions
- Raw field names
- Raw arrays
- GitHub metadata
- File path metadata

Classic HTML rules

- Store classic HTML such as:
  - `<h2>Definition</h2>`
  - `<p>...</p>`
  - `<h2>FAQ</h2>`
  - `<h3>Question?</h3>`
  - `<p>Answer.</p>`
- Remove any legacy `rakos-knowledge-schema` script from existing content during sync.
- Remove malformed legacy wrappers such as:
  - `<p><script ...>`
  - `<br />` inside JSON-LD script content

Schema architecture

- Generate schema during sync from parsed Markdown, YAML, and related-link data.
- Save generated schema JSON to post meta:
  - `rakos_generated_schema_json`
- Treat `schema_json_override` as an optional manual override.
- Validate stored JSON before output.
- Output schema in `wp_head` only for:
  - `is_singular('knowledge-page')`
- Output one schema block only:

`<script type="application/ld+json" class="rakos-knowledge-schema">`

- Do not output schema on blog posts, standard pages, archives, or service pages.
- Do not rely on stored `post_content` confirmation alone. Verify rendered public HTML over HTTP.

Schema generation rules

- Always generate:
  - `WebPage`
  - `BreadcrumbList`
  - `Organization` as publisher
- Generate primary schema from `schema_type` or `suggested_schema_type`:
  - Entity -> `Organization` or `Person`
  - Service -> `Service`
  - Concept -> `DefinedTerm`
  - Framework -> `CreativeWork`
  - Industry -> `Article`
  - Playbook -> `Article` or `CreativeWork`
- Generate `FAQPage` only when the visible FAQ is valid.

FAQ parsing rules

- Parse the visible FAQ section.
- Treat each `h3` under the FAQ `h2` as a question.
- Treat the following paragraph or paragraphs as the answer.
- Stop FAQ parsing at the next `h2`.
- Do not generate fake FAQ schema.

Taxonomy mapping rules

- YAML `type` -> `knowledge-type`
- `related_services` -> `knowledge-topic`
- `related_concepts` -> `knowledge-topic`
- `related_industries` -> `knowledge-industry`
- `related_frameworks` -> `knowledge-framework`
- Create missing terms only when the normalized term does not already exist.
- Preserve exact brand-style terms such as:
  - `SEO`
  - `AEO`
  - `GEO`
  - `AI Search Optimization`
  - `ChatGPT Ads`
  - `Search Everywhere Framework™`

Related link rules

- Related Knowledge should render as visible HTML near the end of the article.
- Link related items only when a safe live target exists.
- Match in this order when building related links:
  1. existing live `knowledge-page` by slug
  2. existing live `knowledge-page` by exact title
  3. existing live `knowledge-page` by `repo_slug`
  4. selected ACF relationship posts when available
  5. approved non-Knowledge live pages for service-style targets
- If no safe live target exists, keep plain text or skip the link.
- Do not fabricate `/knowledge/.../` URLs for pages that are not live yet.

Contextual internal link rules

- Contextual paragraph auto-linking is currently disabled in the sync.
- Keep visible internal linking in the Related Knowledge block until live target coverage is more complete.
- When contextual auto-linking is re-enabled later, link only the first natural mention where appropriate.
- Do not over-link repeated terms.
- Prefer live Knowledge URLs for knowledge concepts.
- Prefer approved live service/commercial pages only when the paragraph is clearly commercial.

Duplicate prevention

- Match existing posts in this order:
  1. `repo_file_path`
  2. `repo_slug`
  3. post slug
  4. exact title within `knowledge-page`

Backup and rollback

- Before updating an existing post, save a backup of:
  - post ID
  - title
  - slug
  - `post_content`
  - excerpt
  - relevant meta fields
- Do not leave malformed schema in content after a failed run if cleanup can be completed safely.

Sync modes

- `validate`
- `dry-run`
- `sync-one`
- `sync-all`

Required live verification after sync

- Check rendered public source over HTTP for:
  - `application/ld+json`
  - `rakos-knowledge-schema`
  - `@context`
  - expected primary schema type
  - `FAQPage` when FAQ exists
  - `BreadcrumbList`
- Confirm the public source does not wrap schema in `<p>`.
- Confirm the public source does not contain `<br />` inside the schema block.
- Run the same sync twice and confirm one schema block only.
- Confirm taxonomy archive pages show the post.

Sync order

- Do not start with concept pages that depend on missing targets.
- Seed live dependencies first.
- Current preferred order:
  1. entities
  2. services
  3. frameworks
  4. concepts
  5. industries, playbooks, templates

Do not do these things

- Do not use Divi dynamic content for ACF arrays, checkbox fields, relationship fields, or post objects.
- Do not publish raw YAML.
- Do not publish Suggested Schema Type visibly.
- Do not publish Internal Link Suggestions visibly.
- Do not append JSON-LD into `post_content`.
- Do not use HFCM for dynamic knowledge schema.
- Do not create duplicate schema blocks.
- Do not assume ACF fields populate taxonomy archives.
- Do not rewrite unrelated site content.
